Media Page for N-Periodics in the Elliptic Billiard

Dan Reznik, Ronaldo Garcia, Jair Koiller

Last update: 2020-07-11 23:18:54

1 Introduction

Videos, applets, images, and code related to our research on N-Periodics in an Elliptic Billiard [4],[1],[2]. For a seminal work on this subject refer to [5]. Triangle Centers of 3-periodics are referred to as “X(i)”, after Kimberling’s Encyclopedia [3]. A glossary of planar geometry concepts is provided at the end of this document, and can be looked up in [6].

Figure 1.1: N-Periodics and their confocal caustics, N=3,4,5

More details about this work are available in a companion page and in the following recent talks/presentations:

  • 7/29/19 IMPA Talk video (enable English subtitles)
  • Talk Slides:
    • 7/29/19 IMPA
    • 9/10/19 PUC-RJ
    • 9/17/19 UFF-RJ
    • 12/3/19 UFMG

2 Envelopes and Evolutes

new On this page we study beautiful curves enveloped by pairs \(X_i,X_j\) of Triangle Centers.

3 Loci of Centers of Ellipse-Mounted Triangles

new Do check out our new page on astounding loci generated by triangle centers when a vertex slides along and ellipse and the other two vertices are held fixed.

6 Interactive Applets

A p5.js interactive applet where you can easily inspect loci and other objects connected with the \(N=3\) family.

Figure 6.1: The loci of X(i), i=1,5,10,11 and the many-cuspid envelope of X(88)~X(90)

To simulate multiple ray bounces within an Elliptic Billiard, try our Mathematica CDF. It requires installation of the Wolfram Player.
